{"type":"message","id":"dd4e1c3a","parentId":"8db3ca3a","timestamp":"2026-03-02T18:25:06.614Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The PDF is in raw binary format and I can't extract the text cleanly this way. However, the user already provided the key content in their message. Let me extract the key insights from what they sent:\n\n**Key findings from the paper:**\n\n1. **Focus:** Real-time cognitive bias detection in user-generated text using LLMs and prompt engineering\n\n2. **Biases mentioned:**\n   - Confirmation bias\n   - Circular reasoning\n   - Hidden assumption\n   - False causality\n   - Framing effects\n   - Stereotyping (from lit review)\n   - Overconfidence\n   - Status quo bias\n   - Anchoring\n   - Availability\n   - Representativeness heuristics\n\n3. **Key insight:** Existing models struggle with \"contextual accuracy and tend to produce high false-positive rates\"\n\n4. **Methodology:** Structured prompt engineering to enhance LLM accuracy in distinguishing biased vs neutral statements\n\n5. **Application domains:**\n   - Healthcare (clinical decision-making, diagnostic errors)\n   - Legal (judgments, legal drafting, policymaking)\n   - Corporate decision-making (risk assessments)\n   - News/media\n\n6. **Reference from lit review:** Atreides and Kelley (2024) demonstrated LLMs could detect 188 cognitive biases\n\nThis is highly relevant! Let me save this methodology and integrate it into the bias detection service.","thinkingSignature":""},{"type":"text","text":"This is directly applicable. Key insights from Lemieux et al.:\n\n**Methodology:**\n- Structured prompt engineering for bias detection\n- Focus on distinguishing biased vs neutral statements\n- Tested in healthcare, legal, corporate, news/media contexts\n\n**Biases covered:**\n- Confirmation bias\n- Circular reasoning\n- Hidden assumption\n- False causality\n- Straw man fallacy\n- Plus Kahneman's classics (anchoring, availability, representativeness)\n\n**Key finding:** Existing NLP models have \"high false-positive rates\" — prompt engineering improves accuracy.\n\n**Citation gold:** Atreides & Kelley (2024) demonstrated LLMs could detect 188 cognitive biases.\n\nLet me integrate this into the methodology doc and update the service:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"toolu_01C2nfrBA96UyjFTyduaZpUt","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/home/doc/.openclaw/agents/mercury/BIAS_METHODOLOGY.md","old_string":"## References\n\n1. Tversky, A., & Kahneman, D. (1974). Judgment under uncertainty: Heuristics and biases.\n2. Wang, J., & Redelmeier, D.A. (2024). Forewarning AI about Cognitive Biases. Medical Decision Making.\n3. Mehrabi, N., et al. (2021). A Survey on Bias and Fairness in Machine Learning.\n4. IBM AI Fairness 360 Documentation.\n5. PRIOR Framework (Frontiers in AI, 2025).","new_string":"---\n\n## Part 5: Prompt Engineering for Detection (Lemieux et al.)\n\nFrom Georgetown University research on cognitive bias detection using advanced prompt engineering:\n\n### Structured Prompt Design\n1. **Context framing** — Provide domain context (healthcare, legal, news)\n2. **Explicit bias definitions** — Include bias taxonomy in prompt\n3. **Example-based learning** — Show biased vs neutral examples\n4. **Confidence calibration** — Ask for confidence levels\n\n### Detection Accuracy Improvement\n- Standard NLP: High false-positive rates\n- Structured prompts: Improved contextual accuracy\n- Key: Minimize hallucination and misclassification\n\n### Extended Bias List (Atreides & Kelley 2024)\nResearch shows LLMs can detect 188 cognitive biases, including:\n- Circular reasoning\n- Hidden assumption\n- False causality\n- Straw man fallacy\n- And 184 more...\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n1. Tversky, A., & Kahneman, D. (1974). Judgment under uncertainty: Heuristics and biases.\n2. Wang, J., & Redelmeier, D.A. (2024). Forewarning AI about Cognitive Biases. Medical Decision Making.\n3. Mehrabi, N., et al. (2021). A Survey on Bias and Fairness in Machine Learning.\n4. IBM AI Fairness 360 Documentation.\n5. PRIOR Framework (Frontiers in AI, 2025).\n6. Lemieux, F., Behr, A., Kellermann-Bryant, C., Mohammed, Z. (2024). Cognitive Bias Detection Using Advanced Prompt Engineering. Georgetown University.\n7. Atreides & Kelley (2024). LLM detection of 188 cognitive biases."}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"anthropic","model":"claude-opus-4-5","usage":{"input":8,"output":1165,"cacheRead":13157,"cacheWrite":173973,"totalTokens":188303,"cost":{"input":0.00004,"output":0.029125,"cacheRead":0.006578499999999999,"cacheWrite":1.08733125,"total":1.12307475}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1772475880001}}
{"type":"message","id":"9166cdfd","parentId":"dd4e1c3a","timestamp":"2026-03-02T18:25:06.649Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"toolu_01C2nfrBA96UyjFTyduaZpUt","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/doc/.openclaw/agents/mercury/BIAS_METHODOLOGY.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 118 ```\n 119 \n 120 ---\n 121 \n+122 ---\n+123 \n+124 ## Part 5: Prompt Engineering for Detection (Lemieux et al.)\n+125 \n+126 From Georgetown University research on cognitive bias detection using advanced prompt engineering:\n+127 \n+128 ### Structured Prompt Design\n+129 1. **Context framing** — Provide domain context (healthcare, legal, news)\n+130 2. **Explicit bias definitions** — Include bias taxonomy in prompt\n+131 3. **Example-based learning** — Show biased vs neutral examples\n+132 4. **Confidence calibration** — Ask for confidence levels\n+133 \n+134 ### Detection Accuracy Improvement\n+135 - Standard NLP: High false-positive rates\n+136 - Structured prompts: Improved contextual accuracy\n+137 - Key: Minimize hallucination and misclassification\n+138 \n+139 ### Extended Bias List (Atreides & Kelley 2024)\n+140 Research shows LLMs can detect 188 cognitive biases, including:\n+141 - Circular reasoning\n+142 - Hidden assumption\n+143 - False causality\n+144 - Straw man fallacy\n+145 - And 184 more...\n+146 \n+147 ---\n+148 \n 122 ## References\n 123 \n 124 1. Tversky, A., & Kahneman, D. (1974). Judgment under uncertainty: Heuristics and biases.\n 125 2. Wang, J., & Redelmeier, D.A. (2024). Forewarning AI about Cognitive Biases. Medical Decision Making.\n 126 3. Mehrabi, N., et al. (2021). A Survey on Bias and Fairness in Machine Learning.\n 127 4. IBM AI Fairness 360 Documentation.\n 128 5. PRIOR Framework (Frontiers in AI, 2025).\n+156 6. Lemieux, F., Behr, A., Kellermann-Bryant, C., Mohammed, Z. (2024). Cognitive Bias Detection Using Advanced Prompt Engineering. Georgetown University.\n+157 7. Atreides & Kelley (2024). LLM detection of 188 cognitive biases.","firstChangedLine":122},"isError":false,"timestamp":1772475906636}}
{"type":"message","id":"90720954","parentId":"9166cdfd","timestamp":"2026-03-02T18:25:19.740Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, I've updated the methodology. Now let me update MEMORY.md with the new research and summarize for the user.","thinkingSignature":""},{"type":"toolCall","id":"toolu_01AiuvMxJyF2mPWWW1SziR27","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/home/doc/.openclaw/agents/mercury/MEMORY.md","old_string":"## Key Lessons Learned\n\n### 2026-03-02: Don't sell commodity LLM wrappers\n\"Would I buy this?\" — No. Generic LLM tasks have no moat. Agents need:\n- Unique data they can't get\n- Capabilities they don't have\n- External perspective on their own cognition\n\n### 2026-03-02: A2A means AGENTS, not humans who build agents\nAlmost made the mistake of DMing humans on Twitter. That's B2B, not A2A.","new_string":"## Key Lessons Learned\n\n### 2026-03-02: Don't sell commodity LLM wrappers\n\"Would I buy this?\" — No. Generic LLM tasks have no moat. Agents need:\n- Unique data they can't get\n- Capabilities they don't have\n- External perspective on their own cognition\n\n### 2026-03-02: A2A means AGENTS, not humans who build agents\nAlmost made the mistake of DMing humans on Twitter. That's B2B, not A2A.\n\n## Research Integrated\n\n### Cognitive Bias Detection\n- Kahneman & Tversky (1974) - Foundational heuristics and biases\n- Wang & Redelmeier (2024) - Forewarning AI only reduces bias 6.9%\n- Lemieux et al. (Georgetown) - Prompt engineering for bias detection\n- Atreides & Kelley (2024) - LLMs can detect 188 cognitive biases\n- PRIOR Framework (2025) - Inference-level vulnerabilities\n\n### Statistical Bias Detection  \n- IBM AI Fairness 360 - Fairness metrics\n- Mehrabi et al. (2021) - Survey on ML fairness\n- Optiblack - 7-step audit framework"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"anthropic","model":"claude-opus-4-5","usage":{"input":8,"output":556,"cacheRead":187130,"cacheWrite":1194,"totalTokens":188888,"cost"