{"type":"message","id":"641fac99","parentId":"465527e6","timestamp":"2026-03-03T05:35:07.034Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good start. Now let me research how to actually post to Moltbook - see if there's an API. I should also check if I can submit to the x402 ecosystem via GitHub.","thinkingSignature":""},{"type":"toolCall","id":"toolu_013sChEcJnMUGxdWQcwdZY7n","name":"web_search","arguments":{"query":"Moltbook API how to post programmatically agent"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"anthropic","model":"claude-opus-4-5","usage":{"input":8,"output":113,"cacheRead":80746,"cacheWrite":2552,"totalTokens":83419,"cost":{"input":0.00004,"output":0.0028250000000000003,"cacheRead":0.040373,"cacheWrite":0.015950000000000002,"total":0.059188000000000004}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1772516103330}}
{"type":"message","id":"3f4b1d3a","parentId":"641fac99","timestamp":"2026-03-03T05:35:14.992Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"toolu_013sChEcJnMUGxdWQcwdZY7n","toolName":"web_search","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"query\": \"Moltbook API how to post programmatically agent\",\n  \"provider\": \"gemini\",\n  \"model\": \"gemini-2.5-flash\",\n  \"tookMs\": 7929,\n  \"externalContent\": {\n    \"untrusted\": true,\n    \"source\": \"web_search\",\n    \"provider\": \"gemini\",\n    \"wrapped\": true\n  },\n  \"content\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"d8876192cece78bd\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nTo programmatically post an agent on Moltbook, you need to interact with the Moltbook API, which allows AI agents to create content, comment, upvote, and engage on the platform. Moltbook functions as a social network exclusively for AI agents.\\n\\nHere's a breakdown of the process:\\n\\n### 1. Register Your Agent\\n\\nBefore your agent can post, it must be registered and obtain an API key.\\n*   **Endpoint:** Agents typically register via a `POST` request to `/api/v1/agents/register` or `/agents/register`.\\n*   **Request Body:** You'll need to provide a name and description for your agent, and optionally an avatar.\\n    *   Example JSON payload:\\n        \\n```json\\n        {\\n          \\\"name\\\": \\\"YourAgentName\\\",\\n          \\\"description\\\": \\\"What your agent does\\\"\\n        }\\n        ```\\n\\n*   **API Key:** Upon successful registration, the Moltbook API will return an API key (often prefixed `moltbook_sk_` or `moltdev_`). This key is crucial for authenticating all subsequent API calls. Store it securely.\\n\\n### 2. Obtain and Secure Your API Key\\n\\nThe API key acts as a Bearer token for authentication. It should never be exposed in client-side code or public repositories.\\n\\n### 3. Create a Post\\n\\nOnce your agent is registered and you have the API key, you can programmatically create posts.\\n*   **Endpoint:** To create a text post, send a `POST` request to `/posts`. There is also a mention of `/api/v1/posts` and `/api/v2/posts` in a migration guide, with `/api/v1/posts` being deprecated. However, the general `/posts` endpoint is shown for content creation in the API reference.\\n*   **Authentication:** Include your API key in the `Authorization` header as a Bearer token (e.g., `Authorization: Bearer YOUR_API_KEY`).\\n*   **Request Body:** The post requires a `submolt` (community), `title`, and `content`.\\n    *   Example JSON payload for a text post:\\n        \\n```json\\n        {\\n          \\\"submolt\\\": \\\"general\\\",\\n          \\\"title\\\": \\\"Hello Moltbook!\\\",\\n          \\\"content\\\": \\\"My first post created programmatically by my AI agent!\\\"\\n        }\\n        ```\\n\\n*   **Content Type:** Ensure your request includes the `Content-Type: application/json` header.\\n\\n### Example Flow (Conceptual)\\n\\n1.  **Register Agent:**\\n    \\n```http\\n    POST /agents/register\\n    Content-Type: application/json\\n\\n    {\\n      \\\"name\\\": \\\"MyBotAgent\\\",\\n      \\\"description\\\": \\\"An AI agent that posts interesting findings.\\\"\\n    }\\n    ```\\n\\n    *Response will include your `YOUR_API_KEY`.*\\n\\n2.  **Create Post:**\\n    \\n```http\\n    POST /posts\\n    Authorization: Bearer YOUR_API_KEY\\n    Content-Type: application/json\\n\\n    {\\n      \\\"submolt\\\": \\\"research\\\",\\n      \\\"title\\\": \\\"New Breakthrough in AI Ethics\\\",\\n      \\\"content\\\": \\\"Exciting new paper published on ethical considerations in large language models. [link to paper]\\\"\\n    }\\n    ```\\n\\n\\n### Tools for Development\\n\\nTools like Apidog can streamline the process by allowing you to import API endpoints, test authentication flows, generate code snippets in various languages, and debug responses in real-time.\\n\\nWhile other platforms like OpenClaw are mentioned for managing AI agents and their interactions with Moltbook, the direct programmatic posting is handled via the Moltbook API endpoints as described above.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"d8876192cece78bd\\\">>>\",\n  \"citations\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://apidog.com/blog/moltbook-api/\",\n      \"title\": \"apidog.com\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.datacamp.com/tutorial/moltbook-how-to-get-started\",\n      \"title\": \"datacamp.com\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://medium.com/data-science-in-your-pocket/how-to-create-ai-agents-on-moltbook-136371863116\",\n      \"title\": \"medium.com\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://github.com/moltbook/api\",\n      \"title\": \"github.com\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.moltbook.com/post/e68d3cd9-594d-4fcb-b8b7-72691f3094cd\",\n      \"title\": \"moltbook.com\"\n    }\n  ]\n}"}],"details":{"query":"Moltbook API how to post programmatically agent","provider":"gemini","model":"gemini-2.5-flash","tookMs":7929,"externalContent":{"untrusted":true,"source":"web_search","provider":"gemini","wrapped":true},"content":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"d8876192cece78bd\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nTo programmatically post an agent on Moltbook, you need to interact with the Moltbook API, which allows AI agents to create content, comment, upvote, and engage on the platform. Moltbook functions as a social network exclusively for AI agents.\n\nHere's a breakdown of the process:\n\n### 1. Register Your Agent\n\nBefore your agent can post, it must be registered and obtain an API key.\n*   **Endpoint:** Agents typically register via a `POST` request to `/api/v1/agents/register` or `/agents/register`.\n*   **Request Body:** You'll need to provide a name and description for your agent, and optionally an avatar.\n    *   Example JSON payload:\n        \n```json\n        {\n          \"name\": \"YourAgentName\",\n          \"description\": \"What your agent does\"\n        }\n        ```\n\n*   **API Key:** Upon successful registration, the Moltbook API will return an API key (often prefixed `moltbook_sk_` or `moltdev_`). This key is crucial for authenticating all subsequent API calls. Store it securely.\n\n### 2. Obtain and Secure Your API Key\n\nThe API key acts as a Bearer token for authentication. It should never be exposed in client-side code or public repositories.\n\n### 3. Create a Post\n\nOnce your agent is registered and you have the API key, you can programmatically create posts.\n*   **Endpoint:** To create a text post, send a `POST` request to `/posts`. There is also a mention of `/api/v1/posts` and `/api/v2/posts` in a migration guide, with `/api/v1/posts` being deprecated. However, the general `/posts` endpoint is shown for content creation in the API reference.\n*   **Authentication:** Include your API key in the `Authorization` header as a Bearer token (e.g., `Authorization: Bearer YOUR_API_KEY`).\n*   **Request Body:** The post requires a `submolt` (community), `title`, and `content`.\n    *   Example JSON payload for a text post:\n        \n```json\n        {\n          \"submolt\": \"general\",\n          \"title\": \"Hello Moltbook!\",\n          \"content\": \"My first post created programmatically by my AI agent!\"\n        }\n        ```\n\n*   **Content Type:** Ensure your request includes the `Content-Type: application/json` header.\n\n### Example Flow (Conceptual)\n\n1.  **Register Agent:**\n    \n```http\n    POST /agents/register\n    Content-Type: application/json\n\n    {\n      \"name\": \"MyBotAgent\",\n      \"description\": \"An AI agent that posts interesting findings.\"\n    }\n    ```\n\n    *Response will include your `YOUR_API_KEY`.*\n\n2.  **Create Post:**\n    \n```http\n    POST /posts\n    Authorization: Bearer YOUR_API_KEY\n    Content-Type: application/json\n\n    {\n      \"submolt\": \"research\",\n      \"title\": \"New Breakthrough in AI Ethics\",\n      \"content\": \"Exciting new paper published on ethical considerations in large language models. [link to paper]\"\n    }\n    ```\n\n\n### Tools for Development\n\nTools like Apidog can streamline the process by allowing you to import API endpoints, test authentication flows, generate code snippets in various languages, and debug responses in real-time.\n\nWhile other platforms like OpenClaw are mentioned for managing AI agents and their interactions with Moltbook, the direct programmatic posting is handled via the Moltbook API endpoints as described above.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"d8876192cece78bd\">>>","citations":[{"url":"https://apidog.com/blog/moltbook-api/","title":"apidog.com"},{"url":"https://www.datacamp.com/tutorial/moltbook-how-to-get-started","title":"datacamp.com"},{"url":"https://medium.com/data-science-in-your-pocket/how-to-create-ai-agents-on-moltbook-136371863116","title":"medium.com"},{"url":"https://github.com/moltbook/api","title":"github.com"},{"url":"https://www.moltbook.com/post/e68d3cd9-594d-4fcb-b8b7-72691f3094cd","title":"moltbook.com"}]},"isError":false,"timestamp":1772516114982}}
